**Enumerations (`enum`)**
An `enum` is a user-defined data type used to assign names to integral constants, making your code highly readable.
```c
enum Day { SUNDAY, MONDAY, TUESDAY };
```
By default, C assigns `0` to the first item (SUNDAY), `1` to the next (MONDAY), etc. You can also assign values manually: `enum Status { PASS = 1, FAIL = -1 };`.

**Unions (`union`)**
A `union` looks exactly like a `struct`, but it behaves fundamentally differently. In a `struct`, every variable gets its own distinct memory space. In a `union`, **ALL variables share the *exact same* memory location**.
```c
union Data {
    int i;
    float f;
    char str[20];
};
```
A union can only store one value at any given time. If you write to `str`, you instantly corrupt `i` and `f`.
